IMPORTANT MESSAGE FROM DISTRICT LEADERSHIP

â€œWelcome to the start of the 2020-2021 school year! We know and understand that families have had to make very tough decisions concerning what type of educational service to provide for their families this school year due to Covid-19 concerns. The schools have been very accommodating for students and families when it comes to scheduling, reassigning staff members, placing members on extended day, and even having staff work with students at multiple schools. Unfortunately, we cannot continue to make daily adjustments like those listed above. With that in mind, this coming Friday, September 11th at 3:00 PM will be the absolute last chance to switch to face to face instruction or online-instruction. Starting tomorrow, any student wishing to change their educational service must contact the administration of his/her school.â€ğŸ“šğŸ’» #teamlaurens #districtleadershipmessage #onlineorinpersonlearning #september11deadline #growinggreatstudents #laurenscountyschools

post_text:
PANDEMIC EBT UPDATE!!!!

All SY2019-2020 enrolled students of Laurens County Schools should qualify for P-EBT benefits as outlined on the flyer below. Parents will receive $256.50 per student.

If your family already receives SNAP benefits, nothing needs to be done. You probably have already received these funds. Only 38% of students who would qualify have signed up so far.

If you do NOT receive SNAP benefits, you must apply at the link on the flyer.
https://dfcs.georgia.gov.
To complete the registration form, parents will need their students GTID. This ID number can be requested by emailing aspensupport@lcboe.net with information requested.

According to DFCS website yesterday, the deadline to apply for P-EBT benefits is September 25. Questions regarding benefits may be directed to local DFCS office or by calling 1-877-423-4746.

https://dfcs.georgia.gov/pandemic-electronic-benefit-transfer

post_text:
IMPORTANT MESSAGE FROM SUPERINTENDENT GARNTO:

After much internal debate and prayer, I recommended to the Board of Education that Laurens County Schools require masks/face coverings in our facilities. "Until further notice, anyone who enters a Laurens County Schools facility will be required to wear a mask/face covering. Masks/face coverings may be removed while eating/drinking/exercising and when social distancing can be practiced. Medical exceptions will be considered on a case by case basis." This update to our Safe Return to School Plan was unanimously approved by our board. I commend them for their support in this endeavor. I understand this will be a challenge for many of you dealing with younger students. I'm sure we all will have opportunities to teach and redirect during these trying times. Continue to stay safe and practice the 3 W's (Wash, Watch, and Wear). If we expect to start and stay in school, these practices are extremely necessary. Thank you for all you do for our students.

Clifford Garnto
Superintendent
Laurens County School System

The local school system is required to consult with home school representatives and private school representatives to share how the proportionate share of federal funds is determined and how special education services and related services will be provided for private school and home school students with disabilities.

Our Laurens County Board of Education will hold a meeting to discuss the proportionate share on Tuesday, July 7, 2020 at 6:00pm at the Laurens County Board of Education. The address is 467 Firetower Road, Dublin, Ga.

Child Find is the school systemâ€™s attempt to locate any children who are suspected of having a disability from ages 3-21. Special education and/or related services may be recommended if a disability interferes with a childâ€™s learning. Speech/Language Therapy, Physical Therapy, and Occupational Therapy are some of the related services that may be offered.

Please feel free to contact Stacey Sanders at 478-272-4767 if you have any questions.

WIFI Access!!!

Outdoor access points for Wi-Fi connectivity have been installed in the front parking lot area of the following locations:

East Laurens High School
Northwest Laurens Elementary School
Southwest Laurens Elementary School

This network is intended for student use. Students will need their lcboe.info account information to access the network. All Internet traffic on this network will be filtered and monitored by LCBOE.

Follow these steps to access the network:
-Connect to the network "AccessLCBOE".
-If a warning screen appears, click Advanced, Proceed.
-Use lcboe.info account information for required logins.
-Non-school devices will require a Securly certificate for
access.

Laurens County School System will offer a credit recovery program this year. Due to COVID-19 restrictions, it will be in an online format only. The credit recovery program will be free to all Laurens County high school students.

Place: Online Onlyâ€¦students must have access to the internet and be available for communication with the teacher during class hours. Remind will be used for communication: text @sumsch20 to 81010 please join as soon as possible.
What classes are offered: Only classes failed during second semester
Price: Free for LCSS students
$250.00 for out of district students

The Mulberry Kitchen
May 4 at 2:39 PM Â·

20 Graduation Cakes for 2020
Graduating High school is one of the most rewarding experiences a person can achieve. Walking onto the stage a child and off of it an adult. We would like to ease the burden Graduation time can have on some parents. Graduation is typically costly. However many of us are living paycheck to paycheck, or NO paycheck at all. We are donating 20 Graduation Cakes to the class of 2020. Nominate your Senior TODAY! We are DONATING no less than 20 Graduation cakes and will continue to donate as many as we can.

If you have Senior you would like to nominate for a Donated Graduation Cake, please email us their information. Hello@themulberrykitchen.com Include their Sr. Picture, Graduating School, full name, and after graduation plans.

If you would like to donate any amount click below.

post_text: What a great partnership we have with Fairview Park Hospital!!
shared_text:
Fairview Park Hospital
April 10 at 8:01 PM Â·

THANK YOU to Matt Taylor, husband of one of our own L&D Nurses, Taylor, for recognizing the need of mask adapters for our frontline staff!

Matt, a 5th Grade Teacher at Southwest Elementary, with the help of Ronda Barnhill Walker, was able to work with Laurens County School District and Grainger Technologies to acquire and mobilize several 3D printers and supplies to print over 165 mask adapters for our staff. These adapters will be a tremendous aid to help protect their ears from breakdown from masks.

Thank you to Matt, Ronda, Macie Pierson, Jason Helton, Cecile Griffin, and other Laurens County school teachers and who are out there, right now, printing these mask adapters for our #HealthcareHeroes. Thank you #TeamLaurens!

The maintenance department had to put down their air conditioning tools, electrical meters, pipe wrenches and carpenter tools to go to the shop and get riding mowers. We had to catch up on cutting the grass on the Laurens County School campuses. The State Department suspended all state detainee details from leaving the institutes for at least 30 days due to the Coronavirus Pandemic. Our Laurens County School System has contracted a state inmate detail to keep the campuses mowed for the past 20 years. They are missed, but we got to do what we got to do. Stay safe everyone!

McKinley Kemp
Maintenance & Facilities Director
Laurens County Schools

#teamlaurens #maintenancedepartment #statedepartmemt #mowers #jacksofalltrades #teamworkmakesthedreamwork #growinggreatstudents #laurenscountyschols

The one thing that steered me towards education was my love for school and itâ€™s activities (sports, prom, clubs, homecoming, etc.). Clifford Garnto

post_text:
Dear Class of 2020,
Yesterday we received the devastating news that we will not be returning back to school for the remainder of this school year. That is not the news any of us wanted to hear; however, it is in the best interest for the safety of our state and country at this time. This news also brings about the difficult decision of having to cancel prom. I share in disappointment with each of you the reality of not having a prom this year, and there is no amount of words that I can write to express my state of disappointment.

I do look forward to the class of 2020 Commencement Exercises that will have to be rescheduled for a later date than the original date of Friday, May 22, 2020. Our compliance to what health and government officials are asking us to step up and do during these tough times will greatly increase our chances of being able to participate in a much anticipated and well deserved Class of 2020 Commencement Exercises at a later date. I pray that each of you are staying safe. I miss and love each one of you!

Educationally,
Dr. Otha J. Hall

post_text:
â€œVietnam Veterans Day commemorates the sacrifices of Vietnam veterans and their families and is part of a national effort to recognize the men and women who were denied a proper welcome upon returning home more than 40 years ago.

The Vietnam War Veterans Recognition Act, signed into law in 2017, designates March 29 of each year as National Vietnam War Veterans Day.

Most states celebrate â€œWelcome Home Vietnam Veterans Dayâ€ on March 29 or 30 of each year. Though there is some debate, March 29 is generally viewed as a more appropriate date. On that day in 1973, the last combat troops were withdrawn from Vietnam and the last prisoners of war held in North Vietnam arrived on American soil. It is also the date President Nixon chose for the first Vietnam Veterans Day in 1974.â€
- excerpt extracted from www.ncsl.org

https://www.ncsl.org/research/military-and-veterans-affairs/vietnam-veterans-day-legislation-and-statutes.aspx

Most states celebrate â€œWelcome Home Vietnam Veterans Dayâ€ on March 29 or 30 of each year. Though there is some debate, March 29 is generally viewed as a more appropriate date. On that day in 1973, the last combat troops were withdrawn from Vietnam and the last prisoners of war held in North Vietnam arrived on American soil. It is also the date President Nixon chose for the first Vietnam Veterans Day in 1974.â€
- excerpt extracted from www.ncsl.org

We appreciate the professionalism of the Georgia Department of Public Safety, as they conducted our annual bus inspections last week. Within three days, they had inspected 109 of our buses and we passed with flying colors!!

Black History Month is recognized nationally during the month of February. This gave several Laurens County Schools the opportunity to pay homage to significant individuals, who positively affected American history. There were many teaching moments and history lessons from every board, book and door decoration. West Laurens Middle School was the most participative school by having a door contest with the theme, â€œOne Act of Kindness Can Change the Worldâ€. They had 99% participation! Kiley Mickel Karmazinas and Amy Price Garnto were named the winners by displaying doors that honored NASA Mathematician Katherine Johnson and embraced the diversity of our students. Thank you administrators, staff, teachers and students for making concerted efforts in providing cultural teaching moments for us all.â¤ï¸ğŸ‡ºğŸ‡¸ #teamlaurens #blackhistorymonth #diversity #worldchangers #growinggreatstudents #laurenscountyschools
